'''Edward Hugh Simpson''' [[Companion of The Most Honourable Order of the Bath|CB]] (born 10 December 1922)<ref>[http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U34934 Simpson, Edward Hugh], ''Who's Who 2014'', A & C Black, 2014; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2014</ref> is a retired [[United Kingdom|British]] [[civil servant]] and former [[statistician]] best known for describing [[Simpson's paradox]] along with [[Udny Yule]].

Edward Hugh Simpson was introduced to the thinking of [[mathematical statistics]] as a [[cryptanalyst]] at [[Bletchley Park]] (1942–45).<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.significancemagazine.org/details/magazine/868559/Edward-Simpson-Bayes-at-Bletchley-Park.html | title=Edward  Hugh Simpson: Bayes at Bletchley Park | first=Edward | last=Simpson | date=June 2010 | volume=7 | number=2 | doi=10.1111/j.1740-9713.2010.00424.x | work=[[Significance (magazine)|Significance]] | accessdate=17 March 2013}}</ref> He wrote the paper ''The Interpretation of Interaction in Contingency Tables'' while a postgraduate student at the [[University of Cambridge]] in 1946 with [[Maurice Bartlett]] as his tutor; and published it in the ''[[Journal of the Royal Statistical Society]]'' in 1951 at Bartlett's request because Bartlett wanted to refer to it.<ref>{{cite journal
|title=The Interpretation of Interaction in Contingency Tables
 | author = Simpson, E. H.
 | year = 1951
 | journal = [[Journal of the Royal Statistical Society, Series B]]
 | volume = 13
 | pages = 238–241
 }}</ref>

The [[paradox]] is used in mathematical statistics teaching to illustrate the care statisticians need to take when interpreting data.{{citation needed|date=March 2013}} It figured in a 2009 episode of the [[United States|US]] television crime-solving series ''[[Numb3rs]]''.{{citation needed|date=March 2013}}

Simpson entered the [[British civil service|civil service]] administrative class in the UK [[Ministry of Education (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Education]] in 1947 and subsequently worked also in the [[HM Treasury|Treasury]], the [[British Commonwealth|Commonwealth]] Education Liaison Unit, as [[Private Secretary]] to [[Lord Hailsham]] as Lord President of the Council and [[Lord Privy Seal]], and in the Civil Service Department.{{citation needed|date=March 2013}} He was a [[Commonwealth Fund Fellow|Commonwealth Fund (Harkness) Fellow]] in the USA (1956–57). At one point a useful observation of his on the aggregate behaviour of teachers' pay was labelled "Simpson's Drift".{{citation needed|date=March 2013}} He retired from the [[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)#History|Department of Education and Science]] as a Deputy Secretary and [[Companion of the Order of the Bath]] in 1982 and now lives in [[Oxfordshire]].

In 2017, Simpson contributed two chapters on the cryptanalytic process [[Banburismus]], developed by [[Alan Turing]] at Bletchley Park during [[World War II]].<ref>Simpson, Edward, Chapter 13, ''Introducing Banburismus'' and Chapter 38, ''Banburismus revisited: depths and Bayes''. In {{cite book| title=[[The Turing Guide]] |last1=Copeland|first1=B. Jack|last2=Bowen|first2=Jonathan P.|last3=Wilson|first3=Robin|last4=Sprevak|first4=Mark| publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] | year=2017 | isbn=978-0198747826 | author-link1=Jack Copeland|authorlink2=Jonathan Bowen|authorlink3=Robin Wilson (mathematician)|}}</ref>

