{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}} {{Use British English|date=September 2012}} {{Infobox musical artist |name = Ruth Ojadi |image = Ruth Ojadi2.PNG |caption = Ruth Ojadi in 2009 |background = solo_singer |birth_date = {{birth date and age|1986|10|17|df=y}} |birth_place= [[Crouch End]], [[North London]], England |genre = [[Jazz]] |occupation = [[Singer]], [[songwriter]] |years_active = 2005–present }}
'''Ruth O. Ojadi''' is a British [[singer]]-[[songwriter]] who appeared in [[BBC]]'s documentary, ''Tourettes: I Swear I Can Sing''.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.tourettes-action.org.uk/news-page/bbc-programme-follows-singer-ruth-ojadi.html |publisher=Tourettes Action |title= BBC programme follows singer Ruth Ojadi |date=28 November 2011|accessdate=2011-12-14}}</ref> She attended [[Middlesex University]] in 2006 but dropped out after two years due to her [[Tourette syndrome]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-16086531 |title=The singer who finds freedom from Tourette's |work= BBC News Magazine |date=11 December 2011|author=Wallis, Luchy |accessdate=2011-12-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/dec/11/young-apprecntice-tourettes-can-sing?newsfeed=true |title=Ruth Ojadi in Tourettes: I Swear I Can Sing |work= The Guardian |accessdate=2011-12-14 |location=London |first1=Phelim |last1=O'Neill |first2=Jonathan |last2=Wright |first3=John |last3=Robinson |first4=Julia |last4=Raeside |first5=Ali |last5=Catterall |first6=Rebecca |last6=Nicholson |date=11 December 2011}}</ref> She also appeared in the Channel 4 show ''[[The Undateables]]'' and is bisexual.<ref>http://www.tourettes-action.org.uk/news-64-the-undateables---ruth-on-tv.html</ref> ==Early life== She was born in [[Crouch End]], [[North London]], England, to [[Nigerians|Nigerian]] parents. Her father went back to [[Nigeria]] when she was two.
